    "Harvey Cox, Henry M. Morris": "Elihu\u2019s Discourse (chapters 32-37). A young man named Elihu (from Buz, probably in northern Arabia) intervenes with an extended and opinionated monologue, contending that he can set straight both Job and his friends. He has little to add, however, that is substantive and nonrepetitious. Job does not answer him, since he introduced nothing new.\n6. Elihu\u2019s Discourse (chapters 32-37). A young man\nnamed Elihu (from Buz, probably in northern Arabia)\nintervenes with an extended and opinionated monologue,\ncontending that he can set straight both Job and his\nfriends. He has little to add, however, that is substantive\nand nonrepetitious. Job does not answer him, since he\nintroduced nothing new.",
